(Correction
    "NOTA records are positional. Wrapping type first, then fields in declared order. The (key value) shape from Lisp/Clojure/JSON is not NOTA. Many agents make this mistake when sketching records in chat without consulting the canonical example."
    "thats not NOTA, and your response is too long, which means it should be a report. … look into how we can get agents to understand nota, simply and reliably - you just made the same misake many agents make in assuming nota has named fields"
    "Correcting my labeled-field NOTA example in chat for the intent log proposal; flagged as a recurring agent failure mode that prompted /231 and the visibility-raise interventions."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T02:00:00Z)

(Decision
    "In NOTA, the wrapping type names the most useful distinction in context. If every record in a file would share the same wrapper, that wrapper is implied — drop it and use the next-level distinction as the type. Data lives in records, not section comments. Enums get names, not numbers."
    "I'm looking at your skills.nota and this is really stupid. You're wrapping every single entry in skill. Obviously we know that all the objects in here are skill. So you're wasting tokens. This is one of the problems with NOTA design …"
    "Critique of an earlier skills.nota that wrapped every entry in (Skill …); produced the canonical three NOTA-design rules now living in skills/nota-design.md."
    Maximum
    2026-05-18T13:07:19Z)

(Decision
    "Add a typed `Path` shape to NOTA whose schema position relaxes the bare-token alphabet. Filepath-shaped content (`/`, `.` in the body) can be written bare when the schema expects `Path`; the quoted form remains the fallback for content with spaces or other unsafe symbols. Same discipline as `#[serde(transparent)]` newtypes accepting bare primitives at their position — the type at the schema position determines which bare alphabet applies."
    "We should create a basic pass type that can either be in quotations if it has spaces or any other symbol that's not safe, but that could also be without quotations. And then we could relax the types of characters that are allowed in a pass type, in a object that expects a pass, so that we wouldn't always need to put pass into quotations."
    "After my investigation explained that filepath strings always need quotes in NOTA (the bare-ident alphabet `[A-Za-z0-9_-]` excludes `/` and `.`), the psyche proposed introducing a typed Path shape with a relaxed alphabet at the schema position. Implemented in nota-codec main commit 97c1f496; spec section landed in nota main commit a0617b99; skills/skills.nota migrated to bare paths in workspace commit 9c018120."
    Medium
    2026-05-18T15:00:00Z)

(Correction
    "The `Said` wrapper I proposed for per-statement entries inside a verbatim vector is superfluous. There is no other variant that fits that position; every entry is a psyche statement. NOTA Rule 1 (wrapping type names the most useful distinction) says drop the wrapper. The correct shape is nested lists: an outer list of statements where each statement is an inner list of positional fields (date, time, quote). Lists don't need a head type; records do."
    "What are the other types, besides 'Said' then? (youre introducing a variant by putting a 'Said' there, you understand that right? otherwise you *still* dont undertand NOTA)"
    "Catching my repeated NOTA mistake: superfluous wrapping. The variant question — 'what else could go here?' — is the test. No other variant → no wrapper. The skills/nota-design.md 'Before you sketch' checklist explicitly says this; I didn't apply it."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19 19:00)

(Correction
    "Agents (me, repeatedly) keep making the superfluous-wrapping NOTA mistake despite the skill explicitly forbidding it. The pattern: when modelling a structured value, default to wrapping each piece in a typed record. The fix is the discipline already on disk: before sketching, ask 'what other variants could go in this position?' — if the answer is none, drop the wrapper. The 'Before you sketch any NOTA record' checklist in skills/nota-design.md is the gate; failure to apply it produces this same mistake every time."
    "you *still* dont undertand NOTA"
    "Meta-correction. The Said wrapper is the same shape of mistake as the labeled-field mistake from earlier in the session; both come from defaulting to scaffolding instead of asking the variant question first."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19 19:00)
